Rockfish utilized coral habitats more than any other, while gravel was the least utilized. Sponge and cobble habitat utilization was intermediate to coral and gravel. Predation of young-of-the-year rockfish by sculpin predators was greatest in gravel habitats and lowest in coral habitats.</dcterms:abstract>    <dc:publisher>Alaska Fisheries Science Center</dc:publisher>    <dc:creator>Malecha, Pat </dc:creator>    <dc:creator>Alaska Fisheries Science Center</dc:creator>    <dc:identifier xsi:type="dcterms:URI">                 https://inport.nmfs.noaa.gov/inport/item/17270</dc:identifier>    <dcterms:isPartOf xsi:type="dcterms:URI">                 https://inport.nmfs.noaa.gov/inport/item/12324</dcterms:isPartOf>    <dcterms:spatial xsi:type="dcterms:Box">                         northlimit=58.4;                         eastlimit=-134.633;                         southlimit=56.035;                         westlimit=-138.158;                                              name=Chatham Strait and Gulf of Alaska;                     </dcterms:spatial>    <dcterms:temporal xsi:type="dcterms:Period">                             start=2005-08;                             end=2009-03;                         </dcterms:temporal>    <dcterms:accessRights>The data set is still being analyzed and will not be available for distribution until it has been finalized and all QA/QC practices have been performed.
